\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Arts of Korea
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 This space reflects Korea as a crossroads where adaptability and resilience have shaped political and cultural formation. Through displays of art dating from prehistory to the present, this gallery demonstrates the innovation within the peninsula as well as relationships and influences beyond it.
\f0\fs24 \

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 Emerging as a unified nation in the seventh century, Korea sits on a peninsula that occupies a strategic location in northeast Asia. This geography has played a critical role in its cultural development and art history. Positioned at the eastern end of the ancient trade route known as the Silk Road, the people of Korea have received, transformed, and passed on artistic styles as well as philosophies and religions. Buddhism, Daoism, and Confucianism have all been sources of inspiration, demonstrating Korea\'92s openness to different traditions and ideas.
\f0\fs24 \

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 The moon jar, a humble yet elegant vessel formed from two hemispheres, has become a national symbol. Its form embodies the quest for a harmonious balance between two opposed yet connected halves. The iconic shape is also a potent metaphor for Korea\'92s modern history as the site of global geopolitical struggles that have resulted in occupation, war, and its division into two linked but separate nations.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
