\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Flip Sides:\uc0\u8232 Seeing Korean Art Anew
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Objects have multiple characteristics and aspects\'97they have many sides. Yet museums and galleries often present a single, carefully chosen view that emphasizes what is considered a work's \'93best\'94 angle. By displaying only one perspective, complex design choices, construction techniques, and utility can go unnoticed. 
\f2\i Flip Sides
\f1\i0  challenges that convention by highlighting the multiple sides of each artwork, inviting viewers to look closely and discover features that are otherwise hidden or difficult to see.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Bringing together approximately fifty objects from The Met collection, more than half of which are on view for the first time, 
\f2\i Flip Sides
\f1\i0  provides special insight into the forms, materials, and styles of Korean art. Using X-ray scans, magnified details, photographs, and atypical display methods, the exhibition exposes interior structures, surface treatments, repairs, and traces of use. These various angles and interpretive tools reveal artistic innovation and technical mastery, encouraging inquisitive viewers to engage more deeply and see Korean art anew.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa106\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 This exhibition is made possible by The Kun-Hee Lee Fund for Korean Art.
