\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 Openwork, a decorative technique featuring gaps or holes, usually appears on small scholars\'92 objects or large garden stools. This Joseon-dynasty porcelain openwork jar is a rare example. Four large peonies with twisting branches form a dynamic sculptural lattice. Incised scrolls at the rim, stylized lotus leaves at the base, and a low-relief scepter motif adorn the surface. An X-ray scan reveals the complex structure within\'97a concealed inner vessel enhances the jar\'92s function and versatility.
