\f1\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Bronze mirrors emerged in East Asia\uc0\u8232 during the late Neolithic and Bronze Ages,\u8232 notably in China, Korea, and Japan. The\u8232 practical objects were also thought to ward\u8232 off evil, symbolizing authority, cosmology,\u8232 and ritual power. Ranging from austere to\u8232 highly ornamented, these examples display\u8232 intercultural connections and advances in\u8232 cast metalwork. While the decorated sides\u8232 are often exclusively exhibited, the polished\u8232 surfaces demonstrate their utility, and the\u8232 interesting weathering and patina reflect\u8232 the marks of time.
