\f4\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Birds and Flowers
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 Joseon dynasty (1392\'961910), late 19th century\u8232 Ten-panel folding screen, silk embroidery
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 Mary and Cheney Cowles Collection, Gift of Mary and Cheney Cowles, 2024 (2024.577.5)
\f0\fs24 \

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 Each of these panels presents two pairs of birds in a landscape\uc0\u8232 of rock and flowering trees, illustrating the intersection of\u8232 painting and embroidery. The finely stitched creatures display\u8232 a wide range of colors, from bright pink and orange to tan and\u8232 black. Flowers and leaves are depicted with articulated veins\u8232 and subtle shading. Inspired by auspicious painting traditions,\u8232 the rocks appear in fanciful blue, green, and purple hues,\u8232 outlined in dark thread. Since textiles are highly light sensitive,\u8232 conservators examined this screen with ultraviolet light,\u8232 causing the pink thread to glow orange (pictured at right and left).\u8232 Together with mass spectrometry analysis, this fluorescence\u8232 reveals the presence of an early synthetic dye developed in\u8232 the 1880s, confirming the screen\'92s late nineteenth-century date.
